## Why Banks Reject Good Malaysian Businesses

You might think, "My business is profitable. Why would a bank say no?"

Here's the reality: Banks operate on rigid criteria that don't always reflect how Malaysian SMEs actually work.

**Common rejection reasons include:**

1. **Less than 3 years of audited accounts** — Many banks won't even consider you without a solid financial track record on paper.

2. **Imperfect credit history** — A single late payment from years ago can flag your CCRIS report and trigger automatic rejection.

3. **No property collateral** — Most banks want you to "charge" a property as security. If your assets are tied up in inventory or equipment, you're out of luck.

4. **High existing debt ratios** — Even if you can afford the repayments, banks use formulas that don't account for seasonal cash flow variations.

5. **Industry concerns** — Some sectors (construction, transport, F&B) are seen as "higher risk" by conservative lenders, regardless of your individual track record.

**The frustrating part?** You might be running a perfectly healthy business with strong orders and reliable customers, but still get rejected because you don't fit the bank's checkbox criteria.

